## Diagnosing and fixing Node.js memory leaks

### 1. Confirm you have a leak first

```bash
node --expose-gc your-app.js
```

Watch RSS/heap over time with `process.memoryUsage()`:

```js
setInterval(() => {
  const { heapUsed, heapTotal, rss } = process.memoryUsage();
  console.log({ heapUsed: Math.round(heapUsed / 1e6) + 'MB' });
}, 5000);
```

Steady climb = leak. Sawtooth (GC collecting) = probably fine.

### 2. Take heap snapshots

```bash
node --inspect your-app.js
```

Open Chrome DevTools → Memory tab → take snapshot, run load, take another. Sort by "Delta" to see what's accumulating.

Or programmatically:

```js
const v8 = require('v8');
const fs = require('fs');
fs.writeFileSync('heap.heapsnapshot', v8.writeHeapSnapshot());
```

### 3. Common culprits and fixes

**Unbounded caches / maps**
```js
// Bad — grows forever
const cache = new Map();
app.get('/data', (req, res) => cache.set(req.url, data));

// Fix — use LRU with a size cap
const LRU = require('lru-cache');
const cache = new LRU({ max: 500 });
```

**Event listener accumulation**
```js
// Bad — adds listener every request
req.on('close', handler);

// Fix — check before adding or use once()
emitter.once('close', handler);
// or
emitter.setMaxListeners(20); // raises the warning threshold if intentional
```

**Closures holding large references**
```js
// Bad — bigBuffer stays alive as long as the closure lives
function setup() {
  const bigBuffer = Buffer.alloc(1e8);
  return () => bigBuffer.length; // closure captures bigBuffer
}
```

**Timers / intervals not cleared**
```js
// Bad
setInterval(work, 1000); // never cleared

// Fix — store reference and clear on shutdown
const timer = setInterval(work, 1000);
process.on('SIGTERM', () => clearInterval(timer));
```

**Promise chains that never resolve**  
Pending promises keep their closure scope alive. Add timeouts:
```js
const withTimeout = (p, ms) =>
  Promise.race([p, new Promise((_, rej) => setTimeout(() => rej(new Error('timeout')), ms))]);
```

**Stream not consumed or destroyed**
```js
// Fix — always destroy on error
stream.on('error', (err) => stream.destroy(err));
```

### 4. Tools

| Tool | Use |
|------|-----|
| `node --inspect` + Chrome DevTools | Heap snapshots, allocation profiling |
| [`clinic.js`](https://clinicjs.org/) | Automated flame graphs + heap analysis (`clinic heap -- node app.js`) |
| [`memwatch-next`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/memwatch-next) | Fires events on heap growth, GC stats |
| [`heapdump`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/heapdump) | Trigger snapshots via `kill -USR2 <pid>` in production |

### 5. Production approach

Add a heap limit to crash-and-restart rather than slowly degrade:

```bash
node --max-old-space-size=512 your-app.js
```

Pair with a process manager (PM2, systemd) that auto-restarts. This bounds blast radius while you track down the root cause.

